TY  - JOUR
T1  - Organization Theory and the Nature of Man
AU  - Gibson, James L.
Y1  - 1966/09/01
PY  - 1966
DA  - 1966/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255121
DO  - 10.5465/255121
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 233
EP  - 245
VL  - 9
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The literature of organization theory can be classified by categories that reflect underlying assumptions regarding the nature of participants in the organizational milieu. The classification scheme demonstrates not only the importance of such assumptions, but it also reflects their dynamic character. By modern standards, the assumptions are seen to be moving toward a more enlightened position; yet, some contemporary literature suggests that the condition of man in organizations leaves much to be desired. The author urges theorists and practitioners of organizational structuring to confront this value-laden issue.
AB  - The literature of organization theory can be classified by categories that reflect underlying assumptions regarding the nature of participants in the organizational milieu. The classification scheme demonstrates not only the importance of such assumptions, but it also reflects their dynamic character. By modern standards, the assumptions are seen to be moving toward a more enlightened position; yet, some contemporary literature suggests that the condition of man in organizations leaves much to be desired. The author urges theorists and practitioners of organizational structuring to confront this value-laden issue.
